<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="385" pageId="3" pageNumber="384" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1538,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,1538,1564]" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Description.</emphasis>
Pale greenish (specimens from old collections sometimes yellowish), usually with more or less developed black pattern on head, pro-, mesonotum, and forewings. In Central Asian populations, specimens with weakly developed pattern or without it prevail (
<figureCitation box="[597,706,1611,1637]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–28" captionStartId="10.[151,264,2000,2024]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,185,1973]" captionTargetId="figure-25@10.[158,1430,181,1976]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 5–28. Macropsis spp., lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4404165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4404165/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Figs. 8–9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1538,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">
Abdominal apodemes of 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[502,518,1646,1660]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">nd</superScript>
tergite in male elongate, sometimes slightly bent inwards, broadly separated by an oval or U-shaped notch (
<figureCitation box="[467,606,1682,1709]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–81" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1893,1917]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-16@15.[173,1413,181,1869]" captionText="FIGURES 48–81. Macropsis suspecta (48–54), M. vicina (55–61), M. tarbagataica (62–68), and M. iliensis (69–81). 48–49, 55–56, 62–63―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 50–51, 57–58, 64–65, 69, 71—the 2nd sternite; 52–53, 59–60, 66–67, 70, 72, 74, 77, 80―penis, lateral view; 54, 61, 68, 75, 78, 81―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 73, 76, 79―male 2nd abdominal apodemes. 69–70―paratype of M. iliensis; 71–72―paratype of M. tuvensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457944" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457944/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Figs. 55–56</figureCitation>
). Sternal apodemes strongly convergent, with wide bases and slightly expanded truncate or rounded tips usually touching each other or even slightly overlapped (
<figureCitation box="[1141,1278,1718,1745]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–81" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1893,1917]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-16@15.[173,1413,181,1869]" captionText="FIGURES 48–81. Macropsis suspecta (48–54), M. vicina (55–61), M. tarbagataica (62–68), and M. iliensis (69–81). 48–49, 55–56, 62–63―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 50–51, 57–58, 64–65, 69, 71—the 2nd sternite; 52–53, 59–60, 66–67, 70, 72, 74, 77, 80―penis, lateral view; 54, 61, 68, 75, 78, 81―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 73, 76, 79―male 2nd abdominal apodemes. 69–70―paratype of M. iliensis; 71–72―paratype of M. tuvensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457944" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457944/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Figs. 57–58</figureCitation>
). Penis in side view wide, with distinct extension in middle (
<figureCitation box="[668,807,1754,1781]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–81" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1893,1917]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-16@15.[173,1413,181,1869]" captionText="FIGURES 48–81. Macropsis suspecta (48–54), M. vicina (55–61), M. tarbagataica (62–68), and M. iliensis (69–81). 48–49, 55–56, 62–63―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 50–51, 57–58, 64–65, 69, 71—the 2nd sternite; 52–53, 59–60, 66–67, 70, 72, 74, 77, 80―penis, lateral view; 54, 61, 68, 75, 78, 81―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 73, 76, 79―male 2nd abdominal apodemes. 69–70―paratype of M. iliensis; 71–72―paratype of M. tuvensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457944" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457944/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Figs. 59–60</figureCitation>
). 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[840,856,1754,1768]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">nd</superScript>
valvulae of ovipositor normally with one preapical tooth each (
<figureCitation box="[282,366,1791,1818]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–81" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1893,1917]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-16@15.[173,1413,181,1869]" captionText="FIGURES 48–81. Macropsis suspecta (48–54), M. vicina (55–61), M. tarbagataica (62–68), and M. iliensis (69–81). 48–49, 55–56, 62–63―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 50–51, 57–58, 64–65, 69, 71—the 2nd sternite; 52–53, 59–60, 66–67, 70, 72, 74, 77, 80―penis, lateral view; 54, 61, 68, 75, 78, 81―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 73, 76, 79―male 2nd abdominal apodemes. 69–70―paratype of M. iliensis; 71–72―paratype of M. tuvensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457944" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457944/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Fig. 61</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1538,2033]" box="[199,942,1826,1854]" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">
Body length (including tegmina): 
<specimenCount box="[580,603,1827,1853]" pageId="3" pageNumber="384" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
, 4.0– 
<quantity box="[665,753,1827,1853]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.4" pageId="3" pageNumber="384" unit="mm" value="4.4">4.4 mm</quantity>
; 
<specimenCount box="[765,786,1827,1853]" pageId="3" pageNumber="384" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
, 
<quantity box="[800,938,1826,1853]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.95" metricValueMax="5.2" metricValueMin="4.7" pageId="3" pageNumber="384" unit="mm" value="4.95" valueMax="5.2" valueMin="4.7">4.7–5.2 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1538,2033]" box="[199,593,1863,1889]" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">
Host. Silver poplar (
<taxonomicName box="[428,577,1863,1889]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salicaceae" genus="Populus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="384" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis box="[428,577,1863,1889]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Populus alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1538,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">
Distribution. Temperate parts of Europe including European 
<collectingCountry box="[905,980,1899,1925]" name="Russia" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Russia</collectingCountry>
(northwards at least as far as 
<collectingRegion country="Russia" name="Moscow" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Moscow Oblast</collectingRegion>
), Northern Caucasus, 
<collectingCountry box="[482,616,1935,1961]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
, Central Asia, southern regions of Western Siberia. Introduced to North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Hamilton, K. G. A." box="[262,444,1971,1997]" pageId="3" pageNumber="384" pagination="875 - 932" refId="ref14095" refString="Hamilton, K. G. A. (1980) Contribution to the study of the world Macropsini (Rhynchota: Homoptera: Cicadellidae). Canadian Entomologist, 112 (9), 875 - 932. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / Ent 112875 - 9" type="journal article" year="1980">Hamilton, 1980</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1538,2033]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1436,150,213]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="385" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">
Widespread in Northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[527,661,2007,2033]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
, where wild Silver poplar grows. The southernmost known locality is the flood-plain of the Ayagoz River 
<quantity box="[590,663,150,177]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" unit="km" value="45.0">45 km</quantity>
southwest of Ayagoz Town, ca. 
<quantity box="[1033,1106,150,177]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="385" unit="km" value="50.0">50 km</quantity>
north of the boundary of the studied region. Can be found in Southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[663,794,187,213]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="4" pageNumber="385">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
on ornamental Silver poplar.
</paragraph>
